Can someone explain to me why "df -h" has 3 swap's mounted - /etc/svc/volatile /tmp /var/run That is what I was thinking but didn't know how to put it in words :) Same reason for this /etc/svc/volatile? looks like it is logs

jlc: those are all filesystems that are mounten in virtual memory, so to say. So you don't have 3 swap's mounted, actually 'df' doesn't even show swap. But all 'ram-filesystems' are listed as mounted in swap.
jlc  solaris put /tmp and /var/run on swap for performance reasons...   data in both those filesystems are useless on next reboot.
and /etc/svc/volatile is needed very early in boot (before /var is mounted) yup.  logs of services which start really early

104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: what do the other two browsers do? so the bullet are on the left of a left float? right but on which side though? left? then i don't understand what you mean by "the line isn't moved to compensate" i guess i don't understand how that differs from float-displace, given the right values of float-displace i have to admit finding it difficult to really care :-) i think we should introduce float-displace and the other property but i've given up trying to make bert and fantasai see reason, so i'm not planning on trying to get any work done in the csswg any time soon what did your patch do? isn't that one of the values of float-displace and company? so what's wrong with the behaviour of other browsers? hm that does suck yeah

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, other browsers make the bullets overlap the floats 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, the bullet is always displaced from the first line by border+padding 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, but the line isn't moved to compensate 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, (see also the three messages I just sent to www-style about float-displace) 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, no, they overlap a left float they're a fixed distance (border + padding of the list item) from the right edge of the left float it's the formula you'd want if you also had float-displace indenting the line except float-displace isn't indenting the line, so the bullet overlaps the float Starting from the beginning, what other browsers do is position the bullet relative to the first line box of the block. or the place that said line box would start if there were one that line box is flush against the float looks for a testcase https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/attachment.cgi?id=302070 it's like everybody's doing the right thing, except without setting float-displace:line on list items which means if we become consistent we'll never be able to change that default whereas now Mozilla is doing something that means float-displace:line would be a compromise between existing browsers so people could move to that default well, float-displace as specced is rather broken but it's easily fixable ok, I guess I'll back out my patch or most of it, anyway it made Mozilla match the behavior of other browsers where the bullets overlap the float but we don't move blocks moving blocks is, but it really sucks I think we want to get rid of it, except for things that introduce new BFCs where it would be the default bullets overlap floats pretty much any time they're next to floats So I don't think I have a good excuse for implementing float-displace this far after feature freeze. But I think I can leave most of what I fixed in. but still back out the change removing -moz-float-edge: margin-box from li

(a) the discussion is easier to follow if a few people are nominated to lead it... and (b) there's an anybody/somebody/nobody risk, and action items are a good way to manage it if you agree to something by email, there's little consequence to not doing it. most people feel pretty uncomfortable showing up to a teleconference empty-handed after they've promised to do something. At least: that's the way I'm used to getting groups to complete work. yes, the agenda has to get sent to the list. let's return to your list of questions... umm... I take that sort of thing pretty seriously. If you agree to do something and then don't do it, I expect some explanation, and I don't let it go unnoticed. There's no way to answer "how productive would the WG have been had we not had the meeting?" This is management, not engineering. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: if we make createContextualFragment create scripts that are script-created and don't have their 'already started' flag set, would you be OK with adding a parameter to the HTML fragment parsing algorithm for controlling script execution prevention? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: it runs the fragment parsing algorithm with a string input and a context node and returns the corresponding DOM fragment 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: it's the Range thing I think insertAdjacentHTML() should prevent execution 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: currently, the main use case is emulating insertAdjacentHTML in browsers that don't have it *yet* 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: but once insertAdjacentHTML is supported, if you think of createContextualFragment  as a standalone feature, it's a shortcut for building a DOM fragment 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: Gecko 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: and if you built the DOM fragment manually, the scripts would be executable so it's illogical for the shortcut to make scripts unexecutable the scripts are executable in Firefox 3.6 and in Opera but not in WebKit 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: only because other browsers cloned IE imprecisely and the execution prevention became the norm for innerHTML that is if I were just lazy, preventing script execution for createContextualFragment would be will hold off on "canvas shadows should not be optional" until there's more than one implementation of them There's a patch which adds shadows to Mozilla (which I wrote), but that was after the FF3 feature freeze so it wasn't included and I'm not aware of any other shadow implementations (...other than WebKit) See http://philip.html5.org/tests/canvas/suite/tests/index.2d.shadow.html if you want test cases :-) (Hmm, Opera (which doesn't do shadows at all) still scores 25% on there...) 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: Ah, sorry, the Safari one is burned into my mind sufficiently that I didn't think to mention it explicitly :-) b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: Web 2.0 needs shadows, not dashes! roundedRect(x, y, w, h, cornerRadius) would be nice too 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: http://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=15266 is the most significant bug http://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=15265 is the only other one I bothered reporting You could argue about what "bug" means when the spec doesn't actually specify the behaviour at all, but I'll stick with my definition for now since I think it makes sense :-) (where "my definition" is http://lists.whatwg.org/htdig.cgi/whatwg-whatwg.org/2007-June/011799.html ) 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: That sounds sensible, since there's nobody to interoperate with yet 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: If you look in e.g. Firefox, you can see what the unshadowed gradient looks like i.e. a square, with some transparent bits around the lower right so the shadow should be the same shape and the same pattern of transparentness, but offset down/right but if I remember correctly, it gets clipped to the source rectangle or something instead of being offset properly 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: How old beta? Might be https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=402527 (assuming you're using a Mac) I can't remember exactly what Safari was doing, and it looks like I don't have screenshots of it Are bugs ever fun to fix? :-) Incidentally, it seems quite trivial to DOS the browser by rendering something with a really high shadowBlur (I clamped shadowBlur to 2000 (i.e. ~190 pixel radius) for Mozilla) tries to find a runnable version of Safari somewhere http://software.hixie.ch/utilities/js/live-dom-viewer/?%3C!DOCTYPE%20html%3E%0D%0A%3Cbody%20onload%3Dwith(document.getElementById('c').getContext('2d'))%7BshadowColor%3D'yellow'%3BshadowBlur%3D10000%3BfillStyle%3D'blue'%3BfillRect(100%2C50%2C100%2C50)%7D%3E%0D%0A%3Ccanvas%20id%3Dc%3E%3C%2Fcanvas%3E 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: That uses a few hundred megabytes of memory and freezes for longer than I can be bothered waiting (i.e. at least a minute) has no idea why that's so inefficient - it should be O(shadowBlur) memory and O(sqrt(shadowBlur)) time, I think guesses that's CoreGraphics's fault

is there really only one? see, I was about to make a test case to make sure I wasn't insane no, I was just pretty sure that the Safari implemenation of canvas did shadows (and that this was the reason it was in the spec) so I was briefly confused when you said an experimental Mozilla patch was the only implementation (Safari does pass only 68% of those shadow tests) (a lot of the failures seem to be for lame reasons though) 'Failed assertion ctx.shadowColor === 'rgba(0, 255, 0, 0.0)' (got RGBA(0,255, 0,0)[string], expected rgba(0, 255, 0, 0.0)[string])' dunno if I'd lose a lot of sleep over that one yeah, the fact that there's good canvas test suites is a plus if I wanted to fix canvas compliance bugs I probably wouldn't start with the shadow stuff I can't tell what is going on in your shadow gradient examples here: http://philip.html5.org/demos/canvas/shadows/various.html (the rest look reasonably ok to me) my FF3 beta fails to render the gradients at all (launching FF2) so we are drawing a solid shadow under the whole gradient filled area I guess? that won't be fun to fix, it is probably a CoreGraphics bug so we might have to hand-code shadow drawing for gradients I prefer fixing bugs that are in code where I actually work on I think we set a limit too, at least for text-shadow so yeah, I'm not gonna click that link :-) but thanks we should probably limit the blur

I'm not 100% sure I understand what you're trying to do (in particular, I'm curious what the itemprop="location" is intended to be part of) in microdata, <li itemprop="location"><span itemscope itemtype="http://microformats.org/profile/hcard"> means the same as <li itemprop="location"></li> ... <span itemscope itemtype="http://microformats.org/profile/hcard"> that is, there's no link between the itemprop=location and the vcard in that case if you have an hCalendar and it contains a vCard, then I don't think foolip's tool will show you the nested vCard (the spec only says to extract the top-level vCards) (e.g. it won't exact Agents either) technically the vEvent vocabulary doesn't allow nested vCards currently iirc http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/complete.html#md-vevent-location says "The value must be text." (as opposed to "The value must be either an item with the type http://microformats.org/profile/hcard, or an absolute URL, or text." which is what the spec for vCard "agent" says) hth the "value" there is the value of the itemprop="" property which can generally be either text, or a URL, or a datetime, or a nested itemscope="" item, s/,$// it doesn't preclude nested markup, but nested markup doesn't affect microdata it's flattened in: <div itemscope><span itemprop="a">hello <em>world</em> how <em>are</em> you</span></div> ...there is a singel item, and it has a single property named "a", and its value os "hello world how are you" with no markup. in: <div itemscope><span itemprop="a"><em itemscope><span itemprop="b">B</span></em></span></div> ...tehre are two _top-level_ microdata items one has a property "a" with the value "B" the other has the property "b" with the value "B" they are not related items -- there's no link between them in the microdata model however, in: <div itemscope><span itemprop="a" itemscope><span itemprop="b">B</span></span></div> there is _one_ top-level microdata item, and it has a property "a" whose value is a nested item, which itself has one property "b" whose value is "B". yeah, that was one of the main goals of microdata the above and itemref="" are basically the two complicated parts of microdata (i recommend ignoring itemref="" for now) 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: my pleasure. When html5lib's sanitizer says things like re.match("^(\s*[-\w]+\s*:\s*[^:;]*(;|$))*$", style) isn't that, like, totally wrong, because it needs escaped backslashes or needs to be r"..."? Oh, maybe not - it seems Python treats "\w\s" identically to "\\w\\s" (Seems fragile to rely on that, though) For today's exciting "you have two problems" quiz: How do you make re.match('^(\s*[-\w]+\s*:\s*[^:;]*(;|$))*$', 'x: y; ' * 20) not take a probably-exponential amount of time to run? Bonus points if the solution is still adequately fast when the input is ('x: y; ' * 20)+'x' a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: It's trying to sanitize style attribute values so it's matching "x: y; x: y" and "x: y; x: y;" (with various whitespace, and limitations on 'x' and 'y') and if it fails to match when it reaches the end, it apparently does a huge amount of backtracking Hmm, that seems a good point - that's where it's going to get the exponential number of matches from Yep, that's what I tried and it seems to make it go fast 57d876083caf517f49e8cf5e03307450: That doesn't stop implementations sometimes taking exponential time to execute them 57d876083caf517f49e8cf5e03307450: Just matching, but in an implementation that does backtracking rather than compiling to a DFA or whatever silly thing computer scientists say you should do

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, ping? so i'm thinking about your [XXX]es that are meant to be like "partial" interfaces and i see that they all only have attributes on them, no operations so that means what you really want is to avoid having a new object in the prototype chain for objects implementing these interfaces e.g. you don't want a new, empty prototype object in the chain that corresponds to the interface with the applets attribute on it but, i don't think "extending" the interfaces, at the IDL level, is the right thing to do you just want to control the JS aspects of it so e.g. if these extended interfaces did have operations, then they would go on to the HTMLDocument prototype object (in this case) well actually i see you have two kinds of XXXes now on WindowModal, where you separate it because sometimes you want this interface to be implemented and sometimes not, but if it is, then there's no extra object in the prototype chain for WindowModal and for the things in the Obsolete section, where they're separate just so you don't see them in the earlier sections but they are actually part of the same interface ok maybe i'm talking myself into allowing "partial" interface definitions for that second case even though it's only because of how you want to organise the spec but for the WindowModal case i think your XXX does need to be something like NoPrototypeObject maybe partial should also exist to support adding new constants from different specs, like DOMException codes also, i'm thinking of moving a bunch of things from extended attributes into the "proper" syntax like optional arguments, variadic operations i'm gonna give up pretending web idl is a superset of omg idl so, having a [NoPrototypeObject] could do that especially if the interface only has attributes, since they never go in prototype objects maybe something like [AugmentPrototype=Window] instead yes, except for other language bindings which don't have prototypes they'd be proper, separate interfaces still yeah? how should it matter? if you say "all HTMLDocument objects also implement HTMLDocumentObselete" oh casting would matter i mean, you'd need to cast hmm so it sounds like you exactly want a "partial" modifier on interface ok i'm gonna go for a "partial" keyword then, see how it goes partial interface HTMLDocument : ... { /* now stuff */ };   partial interface HTMLDocument { /* old stuff */ }; hmm you want any interface to be extendable? right yeah i'm not sure well, not really you can extend with ":" but it's a different kind of extending right depends on how you want the prototype chain to look yeah Window is a bit special in that regard, in that you think of it as just a pool of properties that you add to heh perhaps it's kinda weird for languages like java to have an interface whose definition changes depending on which specs you decide to implement it's different if you want to use two libraries together, say let's say a spec first pfn: Yes, that's legal suedoh_: You don't lose the border, but the two divs go out of normal flow, meaning the wrapper has no reason to be bigger than 0. It collapses. suedoh_: You need something after those divs inside the wrapper to have clear:both pfn: You realize that IE doesn't support :after, right? suedoh_: After content suedoh_: Er, wait, is content inside sidebar-left? suedoh_: And yes, clear:both; It would be after whatever is floated, but inside the container that you want to show up And the clear element has to have some sort of content or height value so it doesn't collapse When something is floated, it goes out of normal flow, kind of like when something has position:absolute. So whatever is after the floated element isn't below it like it normally is. So the container has nothing forcing it to be bigger than nothing, and it collapses. If you put something inside with clear:both, it pushes that element below anything that's floated, therefore forcing the container to be larger

looks at some bits of BGP and sees that it's much more of a disgusting hack than he imagined When a network is advertising a route to another network, it can include a 32-bit number which is conventionally interpreted as two 16-bit numbers, where the first number is effectively a namespace (corresponding to the AS number of some network) And then there's a giant database of routing information (150MB gzipped text) which includes 'remarks' sections saying things like 'if you send a route with community value 6730:1x130 (where x is 1, 2 or 3) then we'll add a weight of x onto your route before advertising it to France Telecom' (except not really as a sentence like that - there's a table with a few dozen of these values) I suppose it sort of works in practice, but it just really doesn't seem very nice at all That feature was seemingly designed to provide distributed extensibility, but I can imagine it would be prettier if they gave you more than 16 bits to store all your data in Aww, how cute, there's one in this database with a little ASCII-art box around their table and a comment saying "Net at Once offer these communities to make the life of our peers and customers more joyful." Surely if this is necessary for good math rendering, and Firefox aims to support good math rendering, it should ship the fonts? Although I realize you have concerns about download size, etc. The SIL Open Font License is very permissive, and should be compatible with the GPL since you aren't linking the fonts. I need to add an API to extract a MediaStream from an HTML media element I have to decide whether the stream should represent "whatever's currently playing in the media element" or "just the current resource, until it ends" in the latter case, loading a new resource or restarting playback after "ended" would start a new stream 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: any opinion? those are all use-cases the latter is less interesting I think my main use cases are audio/video playback with mixing and processing; stream it out to a peer is a secondary use-case the main problem with the "whatever's currently playing" approach is that it means the stream can end, and then start producing data again later the RTC people don't like that if you treat the "ended" state of the media element as ending the stream which would be intuitively appealing, and useful as well then we'd need a different API to let authors load a media resource and get a MediaStream for it that ends when the resource ends we could have both APIs on the media element, but that might be confusing MediaStreams end when they will no longer produce any new data the MediaStream for a resource ends when we've finished playing it back MediaStreams play back in real time, they can't instantly deliver all their data to some consumer at least, the way I understand it sure it does you can't fast-forward a MediaStream you can pause, but not rewind if the user just gave you a File then you can make a BlobURL and just play that MediaStreams need not be involved and then you can do everything defining a media processing graph where you can control the playback rate of individual streams gets very problematic (you end up being able to consume a single stream at different rates, and therefore at different time offsets, which is not really implementable) ok then we'll need a separate API to create a MediaStream for a resource that ends when the resource playback ends any suggestions on where that should lvie? because if it doesn't live on the media element, then we have to duplicate all the source selection logic and probably more, which would really suck I can do that I guess then I have to add an API somewhere to forcibly end the stream people want to add features that trigger when streams end OK precise timing is not really an issue that's a bit ugly disconnecting the stream from downstream mixers, for example ta

hmm what's the use case? pushing to a peer / WebAudio processing? or saving the resource to disk? displaying it in a monitor <video>? if the use case is to take whatever the user is currently watching and essentially fork it for use elsewhere, i'd go with having a "live" copy that just streams whatever is being rendered so e.g. it would start displaying a static image if the media element was paused, etc though that would act really weird if you then could pause and rewind it why would it end? if you're just outputting what the media element is playing, i don't think you'd do that "ended" just means that the current playback position is at the end doesn't mean that there won't be more later well, i could certainly see a use case for "get a mediastream for a resource", but it wouldn't "end", it would just represent the (possibly finite) resource, right? i guess it would "end" when the whole resource was obtained which might be immediately if the resource is cached right so a MediaStream of a finite resource that happens to be already cached would end immediately after providing all the data to whatever consumer exists oh well then it doesn't make much sense to get one for a static resource surely what if the user wants to fast-forward? it'd be really weird to tell the user that he can pause, rewind, etc, but he can't fast-forward ahead of where the mediastream happens to have reached especially if the user just gave you the File in question well to answer your original question, i think if mediastream represents live data and only live data, and you create one from an HTMLMediaElement, it should represent whatever frame/audio is currently playing and it shouldn't ever "end" what's the use case for that one? why wouldn't you just create an HTMLMediaElement that the user can't mess with, and use that to feed the MediaStream? MediaStream.end() if it's the kind of feature where precise timing matters, i guess you could just create a MediaStream from a fixed URL, and screw the source selection stuff if someone needs to pick a source, they can create a <video> and have it do the source selection and then use the result from that not the most efficient, certainly what kind of thing are we triggering on end? 042dd99eb0ff8653814e445ca0093427: oh if it's just cleanup then yeah, i'd go with an explicit .end(). ok i gotta go, bbl

I'm about to write out my idea into a blog post, but wanted to know if anyone else had started work or proposal on this type of thing Most people use Javascript right now to do client-side hashing of things like passwords Like sending some salt and then doing MD5 in Javascript To avoid sending the password over the wire I haven't seen that, but from scanning it sounds like what I'm talking about I see it re-created all the time and thought it deserves a non-scripting solution one important thing is that it should be capable of doing salt Thanks I'm reading the mailing list now HTTPS is broken I can sign PayPals cert... Its obfustication now IMO The failures aren't the same When SSL fails you get the plain text password (Because it was transmitted) If this is broken you at best get a subset of what the password could have been, if you wasted enough FLOPS to break the hash Which also assumes you busted the salting technique ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: You can't use old technology to justify not creating new technology ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: In my proposal the salt would actually not be transmitted over the wire but would be a truely private key, such as when the user registered ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c's scenario would keep the new technology from being created because the old technology can enable a flaw. The old (unsecure) tech should be deprecated ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: All that would be sent over the wire is a hash of the INPUT data and a salt I think you're on a logically slippery slope there A neat solution for that attack would be to force the salt to be based on the content delivered (or part of a composite salt) So the server delivers you content and saves the salt of the content delivered in server session for later verification the document By "replace the content of an external script", do you mean change a script on my host? The hashing wouldn't be done in a script Thats the point of this "proposal" And instead submit to the attacker If something like this was adopted I would expect browsers to warn when sending unencrypted passwords more violently Or deprecated/remove the behaviour Either way I find it hard to justify keeping the behaviour of sending the password as (obfusticated) text I understand where everyone is going with this, but does it really justify continuing to send passwords as obfuscated plain text ? a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c believes that a more secure password authentication that doesn't send the password over the wire, and instead sends a hash, is not worth having because the MITM can just rely on deprecated behaviour ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: I remind you again that SSL is broken I disagree, because we'll be putting faith once again in another technology like SSL, that when/if broken will give access to plaintext passwords again.
